            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-11-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-11-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="36" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d36">
                <head>36. Memorandum From President <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> to
                    the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d36fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 924, VIP Visits, Visit
                        of Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName>, November
                        19–21, 1969, Vol. I [1 of 3]. Secret; Eyes Only. Printed from an unsigned
                        copy.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1969-11-24">November 24, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>As you will note in my final talk with <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d36fn2">
                        <ref target="#d35">Document 35</ref>.</note> he hedged on the use of the
                    word comprehensive. I want you to read the transcript very carefully and then
                    follow up. We have to drive a hard bargain at Geneva and I think <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName> expects us to do so.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
